<font color="#FF0000">CRITICS ANSWERED</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun  9 13:05:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I welcome and appreciate the comments and criticisms that my postings here have generated.  They illustrate perfectly the point that I was trying to make: Most Americans are uncomfortable with the give and take of truly free expression.<br><br>
Please notice that in responding to my critics, I never once attacked or belittled them:<br><br>
    Not when I was compared to Rush Limbaugh;<br>
    Not when a critic, someone who evidently feels qualified to speak for all other visitors, past and future, to this part of cyberspace, suggested that I cease posting here because he was &quot;weary&quot; of my opinions;<br>
     Not even when I was threatened with incineration!!<br><br>
In each instance, I tried to provide information and opinions that went to the heart of the issue, and not to the jugular of any previous contributor.  <br><br>
To those who are offended by my characterizing our Congressional representatives as whores, and the super-patriots that support this amendment, especially the American Legion, as bigots and dangerous fanatics, I say this:<br>
     1] Thank you your lucky stars that you live in a                country where such speech is protected by law; and<br>
     2]Refute my assertions and insinuations, as is your             right and if you can and care to, and in the free           and open debate that ensues, I guarantee you all            that I can provide ample evidence to back up                everthing that I say.  Rush Limbaugh, who carefully          screens out articulate opponents, is never so               fair-minded.<br><br>
This American discomfort with truly free speech, that I mentioned up above in the first paragraph of this posting,  is probably as old as the First Amendment itself.  What Alexis De Tocqueville observed about this country 160 years ago is still true today.  He wrote:  &quot;I know of no country in which there is so little independence of mind and real freedom of discussion as in America...&quot; where &quot;...the majority lives in the perpetual utterance of self-applause...&quot; [Alexis De Tocqueville, DEMOCRACY IN AMERICA, Volume I, Chapter XV, &quot;The Unlimited Power of the Majority.&quot;]<br><br>
And it is just this freedom of discussion that is under attack by the Flag Protection Amendment.  What is at issue here is not whether the flag is worthy of special reverence, but whether the Constitution should be disfigured with an amendment that would allow prohibition and punishment of all opinions to the contrary.<br><br>
Consider the implications of this amendment.  Do some citizens, because they constitute a majority, have the right to bar the rest of us from considering or espousing ideas that they find &quot;offensive&quot;?  And if one idea, like the sanctity of the flag, can be protected from challenge, then why not others?<br><br>
Please remember that the USA was founded by men who challenged, belittled and ridiculed a long-held and sacred idea of their time:  that is, that a nation ought to be governed by divine right by an absolute monarch.  Are we now to embrace a new sacred idea, that the skeptical and critical faculties of our intellects ought to be governed by the special rights and privileges of a textile, and by the sensitivities of those who regard it as worthy only of adulation?<br><br>
That earlier sacred idea, rule by divine right, protected and justified the brutal crimes committed for centuries by the wealthy and powerful nobility, and by their lackeys in the Church, against the peasantry.  I urge all who read this to carfully consider what free speech has done to empower ordinary people, and what may really motivate those who seek to restrict it.<br><br>
Part II:  THE AMERICAN LEGION: ENEMIES OF FREE EXPRESSION<br><br>
For a balanced view of the history of the American Legion and its long and stubborn opposition to truly free speech, consult Walter Pencak's book, FOR GOD &amp; COUNTRY: THE AMERICAN LEGION, 1919-1941.  <br><br>
It amused me to read here that though the Legion has long harassed free thinking people in its pursuit of &quot;100% Americanism,&quot; when challenged to define just what that expression meant, they were unable to do so.  They should have asked me, 'cause I know just what it means:<br>
   &quot;What's best for us is best for America, and good enough for everyone else.&quot;<br><br>
John M. Stassi<br>
Vets For Free Speech<br>
&quot;Protect Free Speech!  Burn the Flag Protection Amendment!&quot;
